## 2026-07-04 â€” Unified response envelope for all REST responses
- What: every internal/handler response and the OIDC resource-server auth errors
  now share one shape â€” success {"success":true,"data":<typed>}, error
  {"success":false,"message":<msg>,"error_code":<code>}. Envelope is the generic
  domain.APIResponse[T] with a flat message/error_code (no nested error object)
  (internal/domain/response.go); generic handler helper writeOK[T] + writeErr +
  refactored writeError (response.go); all handler c.JSON sites converted; oidc
  middleware unauthorized/forbidden emit domain.APIResponse[any] (middleware.go).
  handler.ErrorResponse is a flat doc struct for the swagger @Failure annotations.
- Why: give clients (admin panel / iOS) a single, predictable response structure.
- Scope note: the OAuth/OIDC protocol endpoints (/oauth/token, discovery, JWKS,
  DCR) are intentionally NOT wrapped â€” they must keep their RFC-defined bodies.
  204 No Content deletes keep an empty body (nothing to wrap).
- Files: internal/domain/response.go, internal/handler/{response,connection,
  convert,media,taxonomy,video,novel,health}_handler.go, internal/handler/
  helpers_test.go + media_handler_test.go, internal/oidc/middleware.go
- Tests: go build ./... + go vet ./internal/... clean; gofmt clean; go test ./...
  â†’ 205 pass. Verified wire shape: success {"success":true,"data":{...}},
  error {"success":false,"error":{"code":...,"message":...}}.
- Follow-up (not done): swagger @Success/@Failure annotations still describe the
  inner types, not the envelope â€” regenerate/rewrite in a later pass.

## 2026-07-05 â€” Pagination metadata in response headers (offset + cursor)
- What: pagination data now rides in response headers instead of only the body.
  New domain.Pagination (offset|cursor) with OffsetPagination/CursorPagination
  constructors + domain.CatalogPageSize (internal/domain/pagination.go). New
  handler.writePagination emits X-Pagination-Kind / -Has-Next / -Per-Page /
  -Page / -Total / -Next-Cursor / -Prev-Cursor, and queryCursor parses the
  cursor param (internal/handler/pagination.go). Wired into the offset-paginated
  catalog list endpoints (popular/latest/search). Cursor strategy is fully
  supported by the helper (constructor + header branch + query parser), ready to
  wire when a cursor endpoint lands.
- Why: requested â€” pagination should be readable from headers and support either
  skip/offset or cursor pagination via one helper.
- CORS: handler.PaginationHeaders added to the cors ExposeHeaders (router.go) so
  the cross-origin admin panel can read the headers.
- Files: internal/domain/pagination.go (new), internal/handler/pagination.go
  (new), internal/handler/media_handler.go, internal/service/media_service.go
  (30 -> domain.CatalogPageSize), internal/server/router.go,
  internal/handler/internal_test.go (writePagination + queryCursor tests).
- Tests: go build ./... + go vet ./internal/... clean; gofmt clean; go test ./...
  â†’ 210 pass; internal/handler coverage 88.2% (>80% gate). Verified live: a
  Popular response carries X-Pagination-Kind:offset, -Page:2, -Per-Page:30,
  -Has-Next:true, and omits -Total when unknown.

