## 2026-07-06 â€” Refresh-token rotation reuse-tolerance + apply-all D1 migrations
- What:
  - Fixed the "login mulu" refresh-token rotation race. Rotation no longer
    hard-deletes the old row (non-atomic delete-then-insert); it atomically
    *claims* the rotation via `UPDATE ... WHERE superseded_by IS NULL RETURNING id`
    so concurrent redemptions serialize. Losers â€” and any duplicate redemption
    within a 30s grace window â€” receive the winner's already-minted successor
    instead of invalid_grant, so the iOS app's parallel post-expiry requests never
    sign the user out. Redeeming a superseded token after the grace window is
    treated as reuse/theft and revokes the chain (RFC 6819 5.2.2.3 / OAuth 2.1).
  - Fixed `make d1-migrate` (Task B): it only applied 0001_init.sql, so every
    later migration â€” including the 0006 `source` seed that provisions the enabled
    `griyamedia` source `/v1/sources` needs â€” was never guaranteed to run. It now
    applies all migrations/*.sql in order (D1_MIGRATE_FLAGS=--remote for prod).
- Why: iOS users repeatedly forced to re-login (rotation race) and `/v1/sources`
  returning empty (source table had no enabled rows because 0006's seed never ran).
- Files: internal/oidc/storage.go (rotateRefreshToken/mintForSuccessor/
  claimRotation/revokeRefreshChain replace renewRefreshToken; refreshTokenByValue
  reads superseded_by/at), internal/oidc/models.go (RefreshToken.SupersededBy/At),
  migrations/0008_refresh_token_supersede.sql (new), Makefile (d1-migrate).
- Tests: go build ./... && go vet ./... clean; go test ./... â†’ 297 pass. internal/oidc
  has no unit-test target (test-exempt infra pkg, no existing test pattern), so the
  rotation logic ships without new unit tests â€” noted as debt.
- Ops: apply 0008 + re-apply the 0006 seed to the deployed DB:
  `wrangler d1 execute manga --remote --file=migrations/0008_refresh_token_supersede.sql`
  `wrangler d1 execute manga --remote --file=migrations/0006_sources.sql` (idempotent).
  Alternatively enable a source at runtime: POST /v1/admin/sources (scope admin.write)
  body {"id":"griyamedia","name":"GriyaMedia","lang":"en","enabled":true}.

## 2026-07-06 â€” Fix leaked CDN-base comment producing unfetchable page image URLs
- What:
  - Root cause: `.env` had `R2_PUBLIC_BASE_URL=    # e.g. https://cdn.example.com
    (empty => proxy via /v1/image)`. godotenv does NOT strip an inline comment when
    the value is empty, so it captured the whole `# e.g. â€¦` string as the value.
    `store.PublicURL(key)` then prepended it to every page key, yielding URLs like
    `https://cdn.example.com (empty => proxy via /v1/image)/pages/<id>/page-0001.avif`
    â†’ iOS load failed with NSURLErrorDomain -1002 "unsupported URL". (Hits local/
    tunnel runs that load .env; the deployed container image doesn't ship .env, its
    R2_PUBLIC_BASE_URL comes from the Worker/wrangler.jsonc which is "".)
  - Config fix: `.env` + `.env.example` now set `R2_PUBLIC_BASE_URL=` genuinely empty
    with the explanatory comment moved to its OWN line.
  - Hardening: new `httpBaseURL()` in config sanitizes R2_PUBLIC_BASE_URL â€” a value
    that isn't a valid absolute http(s) URL (empty, whitespace, a stray comment/
    placeholder, scheme-less) collapses to "" so page URLs fall back to the private
    presigned path. A leaked comment can never again become a real base.
- Why: iOS reader every page failed with unsupported-URL; the CDN base placeholder
  comment leaked in as the actual base URL.
- Files: internal/config/config.go (httpBaseURL + apply to R2.PublicBaseURL, net/url
  import), internal/config/config_test.go (new, 11 cases), .env, .env.example.
- Tests: go build ./... && go vet ./internal/config clean; new config test 11/11 pass;
  go test ./internal/... â†’ 308 pass.
- Ops: code+config only. For the DEPLOYED server, no redeploy is needed unless a
  bad R2_PUBLIC_BASE_URL was set as a Worker var/secret â€” verify it is empty:
  `wrangler secret list` / check wrangler.jsonc vars (already "") and any
  `wrangler secret put R2_PUBLIC_BASE_URL` override. For local dev via tunnel the
  fixed `.env` takes effect on next `make run-server`.

